"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804374","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-14","<p>Our approach to shared care is to amend the maintenance calculation if the child in a case spends more than 52 nights a year at the same address as the non-resident parent. This is to recognise the additional costs directly borne by a parent to be able to provide shared care, such as having an extra bedroom in which the child can stay.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to expand the shared care allowance to include overnight care that grandparents and other family carers provide as the responsibility lies with the non-resident parent to pay the maintenance liability.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-12-14T13:04:11.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804374/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804374/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-11","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will direct the Child Maintenance Service to recognise care provided by grandparents and other family carers when calculating maintenance payments for parents who share the care of their children.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","118578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804375","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-14","<p>DWP is working towards delivering all customer services fully supported by computer systems in which non-digital services, based on customer needs, are kept to a minimum. However, at any point in time we will have a varying number of cases that are maintained clerically, for an average period of 4-6 weeks, while a system fault is being fixed for example and we currently maintain approximately 200,000 Industrial Injury Disablement Benefit cases clerically, although payments for these cases are managed using an existing computer system. There are currently no plans to further develop a technology system to process and maintain Industrial Injury Disablement Benefit cases.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-12-14T13:02:20.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804375/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804375/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-11","Department for Work and Pensions: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many individuals currently have their records with his Department recorded clerically; and what steps his Department is taking to move clerical records to computer systems.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","118576"
