ncy branches have closed in the last five years; how many employees each branch that closed in the last five years had at the time of closure; and which branches are planned to close in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","118667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804465","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-19","<p>Information on the number of permanent and temporary Valuation Office Agency (VOA) staff at each office, previous office closures, and relative staff numbers for each closing office together with details of the remaining open offices following each office closure can be found in the attached document.</p><p>For information on VOA offices due to close within the next five to seven years, I refer the honourable member to the supplementary information provided to the House of Commons Library for Parliamentary Questions UIN 117327: VOA Closures and UIN 117328: VOA Staff.</p><p> </p><p>The VOA's estates programme is transforming the way it uses its offices to support new and more efficient ways of working. It balances affordability and geographic coverage. By consolidating into a smaller number of higher-quality buildings, the VOA will be able to support its staff in adapting to a more flexible way of working, delivering services to its customers in a more cost-effective and sustainable way.</p><p> </p><p>As the VOA reduces its office space, it will take every practical step to avoid compulsory job losses as a result of any future location changes. The VOA will seek, where possible, to retain staff and their skills. Where it is not possible for staff to continue to work for the VOA, it will support them in seeking alternative employment in the civil service or elsewhere.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","118665 ; 118667","2017-12-19T14:23:22.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804465/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804465/answer","Information for PQvoasuppinfo.docx","VOA staff numbers and office closures ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804465/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-11","Valuation Office Agency: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which Valuation Offices (a) have been earmarked for closure and (b) have closed in each of the last seven years; and which Valuation Offices were operational for each of those years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","118668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804466","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-19","<p>All premiums due to date under the contract have been paid. Payments by franchised operators are published by ORR annually and can be found on their website. From 2020 there will be a new public private partnership on the East Coast, the East Coast Partnership, one of the first of a new generation of integrated regional rail operations. This will include appropriate contributions from the new private partner under a long-term competitively procured contract.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-19T11:58:05.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804466/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804466/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-11","East Coast Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 11 of Stagecoach Group plc’s analyst and investor presentation of 27 November 2014 on award of the Inter City East Coast franchise, what effect the recent changes to the franchise agreement will have on the sum of £2.3 billion which Stagecoach Transport Holdings Limited and Virgin Holdings Limited intended to pay the Government in real terms premium payments between 2014 and 2023; and what the value was of each such payment received by his Department to date.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","118669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804467","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-19","<p>Since 2015 the East Coast Main Line Company Limited (trading as Virgin Trains East Coast) has on average, contributed 20% more per rail period to the tax payer than when the franchise services were operated by Directly Operated Railways between 2009 and 2015.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-19T11:54:29.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804467/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804467/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-11","East Coast Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the rate of return to the public purse was on the East Coast Main Line (a) in each year from November 2009 to February 2015 and (b) from March 2015 to date.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","118670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804468","Home Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>The Director General of UKVI responded on 12 December.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-12-13T17:34:31.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804468/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804468/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-11","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to respond to the letter of 8 September 2017 from the Member for Glasgow Central on a constituent, Velayutham Ahilan.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","118671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804469","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-14","<p>The Secretary of State and junior ministers have had meetings with various Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs), including those for North Yorkshire, Sussex, Hertfordshire, Northumbria and Thames Valley, to discuss matters relating to the Criminal Justice System (CJS). Amongst the topics discussed have been their ambitions for greater devolution in the CJS.</p><p> </p><p>Together with the Home Office, Ministry of Justice officials are exploring how PCCs and Mayors with PCC powers can play a greater role in the wider CJS. The strengths that PCCs currently bring to policing could be of real benefit to the wider CJS, and we are keen to explore this further.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-12-14T09:59:17.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804469/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804469/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-11","Police and Crime Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with Police and Crime Commissioners about devolving justice powers locally.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","118672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804470","Home Office","false","2017-12-14","<p>The Home Secretary has regular meetings with Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) where a range of topics, including the extension of the PCC role, are discussed.</p><p>Together with the Ministry of Justice, Home Office officials are exploring how PCCs and Mayors with PCC powers could play a greater role in the wider Criminal Justice system (CJS). The strengths that PCCs currently bring to policing – transparency, accountability and a direct local mandate – could be of real benefit to the wider CJS.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-12-14T16:39:35.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804470/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804470/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-11","Police and Crime Commissioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with Police and Crime Commissioners on devolving further powers to local areas.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","118673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804471","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-18","<p>The latest information available on initial Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) claims to March 2017 and the outcomes following an ESA Work Capability Assessment is published here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment</a></p><p> </p><p>The information for ESA initial claims and outcomes for April 17 onwards is not yet available but will be published in due course.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-18T12:01:03.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804471/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804471/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-11","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have both (a) started their claim to and (b) been placed into the Employment Support Allowance work-related activity group since 3 April 2017 inclusive.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","118674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804472","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-19","<p>The Government has no plans to replace the UFO desk.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-12-19T15:01:26.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804472/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804472/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-11","Unidentified Flying Objects","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government plans to replace the UFO desk; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","118675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804473","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-18","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Leeds North West, Alex Sobel, on 11 December 2017, PQ UIN 117908.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-18T16:05:16.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804473/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804473/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-11","Industry: Natural Resources","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the reference in the Government's Industrial Strategy to protecting and enhancing all aspects of natural capital applies to such capital in other countries that might be affected by decisions made by the UK.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","118676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804474","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-19","<p>The modelling used to derive the changes in annual final energy consumption in 2032, relative to the existing policies scenario did not differentiate between different types of biomass fuels. The figure in Table 11 of the Clean Growth Strategy can be taken to represent a mixture of biogenic fuels, including woody biomass, waste and other sources however we have not made an estimate of which proportion will come specifically from woody biomass.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-19T16:42:52.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804474/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804474/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-11","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the proportion of the 36 per cent increase in the use of bioenergy referred to in the Clean Growth Strategy which the Government plans to come from woody biomass.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","118677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804475","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-19","The Government’s ambition is to ensure universal access to broadband at minimum speeds of 10Mbps by 2020, so that no home or business is left behind. We are considering the best route to deliver universal broadband, whether to introduce a new regulatory broadband Universal Service Obligation, or whether to accept BT’s voluntary offer. We will make an announcement on our proposed approach shortly.","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-19T09:50:33.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804475/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804475/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-11","Broadband: Universal Service Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of whether BT Group’s voluntary offer to deliver a universal service obligation in broadband will deliver universal 10mbps coverage across the UK by 2020.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","118678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804476","Department for Education","false","2017-12-14","<p>The number of pupils, at the end of key stage 4<sup>1</sup>, who were in receipt of free school meals<sup>2</sup>, achieving A*-C in English and maths<sup>3</sup> in Ashfield constituency can be found in the attached table.</p><p>The number of pupils, at the end of key stage 4<sup>1</sup>, who were not in receipt of free school meals<sup>2</sup>, achieving A*-C in English and maths<sup>3</sup> in Ashfield constituency can be found in the attached table.</p><ol><li>Pupils are identified as being at the end of key stage 4 if they were on roll at the school and in year 11 at the time of the January school census for that year. Age is calculated as at 31 August for that year, and the majority of pupils at the end of key stage 4 were age 15 at the start of the academic year. Some pupils may complete this key stage in an earlier or later year group.</li><li>Free school meal eligibility is taken from the census record for that academic year. Some pupils will have no free school meal eligibility information and have been excluded from this measure.</li><li>In line with secondary performance measures and early entry policy, discounting has been applied. More information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/key-stage-4-qualifications-discount-codes-and-point-scores" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/key-stage-4-qualifications-discount-codes-and-point-scores</a>.</li></ol>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-14T17:52:38.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804476/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804476/answer","118679 - table attachment.docx","118679 - table attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804476/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-11","GCSE: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of pupils in Ashfield constituency who achieved a grade A* to C in GCSE (a) English and (b) maths, (i) were and (ii) were not in receipt of free school meals in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","118679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804477","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-19","<p>The Government Hospitality wine cellar is currently self-financing. New purchases are funded from sales of older stock. We do not anticipate that the costs of the small-scale purchases made for the cellar will be significantly affected by the departure of the UK from the EU. In 2016-17, 49% of purchases by volume were of English wines.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-12-19T16:55:13.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804477/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804477/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-11","Government Hospitality: Wines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on the cost of purchases for the Government Hospitality Wine Cellar.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","118680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804478","Department for Education","false","2017-12-14","<p>Ofsted inspection data shows the number and proportion of children in Ashfield constituency who were eligible for free school meals (FSM), that attended a primary school rated ‘Good’ in each of the last three years are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>· As at August 31, 2015 there were 1,327 eligible for FSM of which 80% were in good schools.</p><p>· As at August 31, 2016 there were 1,302 eligible for FSM of which 78% were in good schools.</p><p>· As at August 31, 2017 there were 1,121 eligible for FSM of which 81% were in good schools.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted inspection data shows the number and proportion of children in Ashfield constituency who were eligible for FSM, that attended a primary school rated ‘Outstanding’ in each of the last three years are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>· As at August 31, 2015 there were 1,327 eligible for FSM of which 5% were in outstanding schools.</p><p>· As at August 31, 2016 there were 1,302 eligible for FSM of which 5% were in outstanding schools.</p><p>· As at August 31, 2017 there were 1,121 eligible for FSM of which 6% were in outstanding schools.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-14T17:44:41.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804478/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804478/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-11","Primary Education: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in Ashfield constituency who were eligible for free school meals attended a primary school rated (a) good and (b) outstanding by Ofsted in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","118681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804479","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-14","<p>The contracts for the provision of Officers' and Sergeants' messes and related services are held by a number of individuals across the Department. Some of the contracts are held centrally within our broader soft facilities management contracts and others are held locally by the individual establishments. Local arrangements are in place for end-users to access contracts by request.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-12-14T17:03:42.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804479/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804479/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-11","Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, who in the government holds the contracts for the  provision of officers’ and sergeants’ messes; and what arrangements are in place for end-users to access those contracts.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","118682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804480","Department for Education","false","2017-12-14","<p>Ofsted inspection data shows the number and proportion of children in Ashfield constituency who were eligible for free school meals (FSM), that attended a secondary school rated ‘Good’ in each of the last three years are as follows:</p><ul><li>As at August 31, 2015 there were 650 eligible for FSM of which, 76% were in good schools.</li><li>As at August 31, 2016 there were 696 eligible for FSM of which, 78% were in good schools.</li><li>As at August 31, 2017 there were 821 eligible for FSM of which, 100% were in good schools.</li></ul><p>Ofsted inspection data shows there were no children in Ashfield constituency who were eligible for free school meals, that attended a secondary school rated ‘Outstanding’ in each of the last three years.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-14T17:39:31.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804480/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804480/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-11","Secondary Education: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in Ashfield constituency who were eligible for free school meals attended a secondary school rated (a) good and (b) outstanding by Ofsted in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","118683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804481","Department of Health","false","2017-12-14","<p>Data is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for 999 call handlers on how to respond to callers who are feeling suicidal is developed and delivered by each local ambulance trust, informed by the Mental Health Care Crisis Concordat. This sets out the principles and good practice that should be followed by health staff, police officers and approved mental health professionals when working together to help people in a mental health crisis.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","118685 ; 118712","2017-12-14T11:20:49.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804481/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804481/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-11","Emergency Calls: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of 999 calls received each year from or concerning a person who is feeling suicidal.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","118684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804482","Department of Health","false","2017-12-14","<p>Data is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for 999 call handlers on how to respond to callers who are feeling suicidal is developed and delivered by each local ambulance trust, informed by the Mental Health Care Crisis Concordat. This sets out the principles and good practice that should be followed by health staff, police officers and approved mental health professionals when working together to help people in a mental health crisis.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","118684 ; 118712","2017-12-14T11:20:49.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804482/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804482/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-11","Emergency Calls: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of 999 calls received from or concerning a person who is feeling suicidal are responded to by (a) an ambulance, (b) the police, (c) the fire brigade and (d) other emergency services.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","118685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804483","Department for Education","false","2017-12-14","<p>The number of pupils, at the end of Key Stage 2, who were eligible for free school meals<sup>1</sup>, reaching the expected standard in reading, writing and mathematics in Ashfield and Mansfield can be found in the attached table.</p><p>The 2015/16 Key Stage 2 assessments were the first to assess the new, more challenging National Curriculum, introduced in 2014. Due to the changes to the curriculum, figures from 2015/16 are not comparable to those for earlier years.</p><p>The number and percentage of pupils in Nottinghamshire reaching the expected standard is published in the departments statistical first release, found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-key-stage-2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-key-stage-2</a> (select the ‘revised’ publication for each year and then download the local authority tables). The figures for 2017 will be published on 14 December.</p><p> </p><ol><li>Free school meal eligibility is taken from the census record for that academic year. Some pupils will have no free school meal eligibility information and have been excluded.</li></ol>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-14T17:54:58.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804483/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804483/answer","118686 - table attachment.docx","118686 table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804483/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-11","Education: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in (a) Ashfield, (b) Mansfield and (c) Nottinghamshire who are eligible for free school meals reached the expected standard in (i) reading, (ii) writing and (iii) maths at the end of Key Stage 2 in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","118686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804484","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-14","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs records the numbers of applicants for Tax-Free Childcare, and the children that they have applied for. HMRC also records eligibility information provided by parents in the application and reconfirmation processes. Eligibility information is checked against a range of Government data sources.</p><p> </p><p>Tax-Free Childcare is currently available to working families whose youngest child was born on or after 24 November 2011. It will be rolled out to all eligible parents of children aged under 12 by the end of March 2018.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","118691","2017-12-14T12:42:02.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804484/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804484/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to  the Answers of 28 November to Question 115530 and Question 115536, what information his (a) his Department and (b) other Government Departments hold on the number of households who have applied for tax-free childcare through the childcare choices website.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","118687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804485","Department for Education","false","2017-12-19","<p>We have not yet made a decision on the future of the Collective Spirit Free School site in Oldham. We are currently working with local partners and assessing a number of options for the future use of the site.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-19T15:08:09.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804485/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804485/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-11","Collective Spirit Free School Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans his Department has for the former Collective Spirit Free school site in Chadderton, Oldham.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","118688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804486","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-18","Ofcom plans to publish its assessment of whether Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) have met their licence obligations once it has assessed MNO compliance in early 2018.","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-18T11:33:01.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804486/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804486/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-11","Mobile Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether Ofcom’s assessment of whether mobile providers have achieved their 90 per cent target for land mass coverage by the end of 2017 will be published; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","118689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804487","Department of Health","false","2017-12-19","<p>The Government is in discussions with the devolved administration as they work with social care sector representatives to better understand the impact of these liabilities in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State receives representations on many issues, including regarding social care, but we have not identified any representations specifically relating to this issue.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has an ongoing dialogue with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on many issues.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","118653 ; 118656 ; 118659","2017-12-19T17:45:20.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804487/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/804487/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-11","Social Services: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer about the sustainability of the social care sector in Northern Ireland when providers and those in receipt of personal budgets have to fund historical liabilities for sleep-in shifts.","false","Biography information for Emma Little Pengelly","Belfast South","Emma Little Pengelly","118657"
